I've seen how much print quality increases with dual fan ducts.   
I've also long been envious of the Ultimaker 2's dual fan ducts.  
I'm no longer envious...

Adding a second fan-duct and fan will require a few extra parts and some soldering.
  • Get a proper heat sink for the 12V voltage regulator on the UM motherboard. The extra current draw from a second fan will cause this part to heat up even more than usual. You risk burning it out without one.
  • Make (solder) a parallel Y connector to connect to the existing cooling fan wire at the hot end. Then the 2 fans can be connected in parallel to the branches. It helps to get some M/F connectors to make connection and disconnection easier.
    • Heat conduction to the fan duct is quite strong nearest the heater block. PLA will go quite soft due to the low glass-transistion temperature. ABS might be a better alternative for this application.
    I'm stuck with PLA for the time being so I use a zip tie to reduce the sag. This approach has worked nicely for some time now.

comments.text: The spacer is some plywood to thermally insulate the duct from the mounting plate. Heat transfer is limited to the bolts. I put a spacer (piece of tubing) at the top of the bolts beneath thumbscrews, so there is less turning to remove the bolts - less  effort/excess thread to remove them. No trimming required.

description.text:
Photography with crystal balls is a "thing" these days -- but how to hold your ball when taking scenic photographs?

Attach this gadget to an Arca-Swiss (or similar) baseplate, and it will cradle a crystal ball on top of a photographic tripod for you. The design includes 1/4"-20 threads, so you could just screw it on / off a tripod's top if you chose -- but since I'm not sure how long plastic threads would hold up in this way, I'd recommend you mount it once to a tripod plate and then you're done. The cup is 40mm in diameter -- just the right size for narrow (20mm or 25mm) Arca-Swiss baseplates, and shaped to hold crystal balls 60mm in diameter or larger.

title: Simon's Omnidirectional 4-wheeled Robot (modified Robodyssey Mouse)
license: Creative Commons - Attribution - Non-Commercial - Share Alike

description.text: My student, Simon Shao, made this to fit on the chassis of the Mouse robot by Robodyssey Systems (http://www.robodyssey.com/teensy-mouse-kit/). Normally the Mouse is a two-wheeled robot, but with these wheels, hubs, and servo mounts, the Mouse robot becomes an omnidirectional vehicle, which can move in any direction. See it here on YouTube: http://youtu.be/jVVpeu6Htxc. UPDATE: Users now have the option to print servo mounts and wheel hubs either with or without brass inserts. With brass inserts, the 4-40 and 8-32 mounting screws bite into the metal inserts, allowing them to be inserted and removed many times without damaging the plastic. However, some may not want to buy the extra hardware, so another version is now available that does not require the brass inserts. Instead, the screws can be inserted directly into the plastic, which is fine if the screws will not be removed often. (The latter option requires that the holes be tapped or self-tapping screws used.)

Simon and I printed these with a MakerBot Replicator 2 at low resolution (0.3mm/layer). The conical wheel sections have 2 shells and something like 15% infill. The wheel hub and servo motor mounts were printed with 3 shells and 25% infill. Only the bottom portion of the servo mount is required. Again, it is designed to fit to the body of the Robodyssey Mouse robot (http://www.robodyssey.com/teensy-mouse-kit/). The top portion adds some stability and gives two mounting holes on each side for a Sharp Infrared sensor (http://www.robodyssey.com/sharp-2yoa21-infrared-ranging-sensor/) The wheels require a 4mm aluminum rod to serve as the axle rod. We ordered this from McMaster-Carr (http://www.mcmaster.com part number 1681T22) and cut each axle down to 35mm. For traction, each wheel needs one large o-ring (3mm, 29mm ID), although dipping the wheel in liquid rubber may also work. The o-ring was also purchased from McMaster-Carr (http://www.mcmaster.com part number 9262K742). It is recommended that a small washer be inserted between the wheel and the wheel hub to prevent the plastic parts from rubbing. The size of the washer depends on which file you download.
  • If you print the hub whose file name includes the words "tap holes" then use a 4.3mm ID washer, for example 93475A230 from http://www.mcmaster.com.
  • If you print the hub whose file name includes the words "brass inserts" you will need a 5.3mm ID washer so that it fits over the nylon spacer, for example http://www.mcmaster.com part number 91166A270. (In a pinch, the latter washer will work for either hub.)
    • The servos are attached to the printed servo mounts with 8-32 screws. The wheel hubs are attached to a servo horn with 4-40 screws. (If you want to attach a Sharp IR sensor to the servo mount, 4-40 screws are also used for that.) UPDATE: You now have two options to choose from regarding the servo mount and wheel hub. The files that include the words "tap holes" can be printed and used as is -- no additional hardware (other that that listed above) is required. However, you will need to tap the holes for 4-40 and 8-32 screws or use self-tapping screws. The files that include the words "brass inserts" require the purchase of additional hardware. The brass inserts allow the screws to bite into metal rather than plastic. (This option also makes use of nylon inserts on the wheel hub so the metal axle spins more smoothly.) The additional hardware are as follows:

  • Threaded brass inserts. Instead of tapping holes directly into the plastic, we find it is better to use threaded brass inserts, especially if the servos and the hubs are to be removed often. As you might guess, these are from McMaster-Carr (http://www.mcmaster.com part numbers 92395A114 (for 8-32 screws) and 92395A112 (for 4-40 screws)).

  • Nylon spacer. This spacer fits in the large holes on the end of each arm of the wheel hub. The thinking was the smooth inner wall would reduce friction of the axle rod and support a metal washer between the wheel and hub arm. (http://www.mcmaster.com part number 93657A857). [* If you have some cash to spend, then forget this nylon spacer and purchase a double shielded ballbearing casing (http://www.mcmaster.com part number 7804K1) which spins like butter. The last wheel inserted will be a tight fit, though!]

description.text:
Replacement for the x-axis fishing line with a T2.5 belt and 608 bearing. My X-Axis line isn't proper installed so from time to time they jumped out and i have to fix it.
Insted to fix this problem i saw on thingiverse that another user replaced the x-axis with a belt.[ http://www.thingiverse.com/thing:194686 ]
unfortunately i hadn't such small bearing at home, so my journey starts...

Remove the sand paper and drop the puelley on the motor.
With a small hammer place the 2 608 bearing on the x-base.
Replace the plate for the X-Axis motor with the printed part: x-base. i had to use a rasp to fit the x-base into the printer. Cut the 2 mikey mouse ear from the wooden plate near to the stepper motor. this is necessary to have to full X path. The 608 bearing are so big that you would lose about 3cm each side.
have a look at the draft in the gallery.
Drill 3mm 2 holes to fix the end stop on both side. One hole is for the wooden bed the other hole is for fixing the end stop.
Have a look at the 4th pciture from the gallery. Put the belt into the puelly and bearing like the picture and screw it down with the end stop nr 2.
move the board and test if the belt staying on the bearing. To assemble the bed you need longer screws about 40mm length.

description.text:
This is a customisable recreation of Devin Montes' (@MakeAnything) Cubemail design.
His video about fabrics: Experimenting with 3D Printed Fabric (youtube) - this type of fabric is presented at around 3:30 in the video.
Original design: https://www.myminifactory.com/object/cubemail-bowl-49476

This fabric is really fluffy and works in a lot of different sizes (I got it a lot smaller than in Devins video). But if you make the gaps too small it will become stiff.
It's just fun to play with a small sample of this fabric but of course it might be used to create clothing parts or bracelets.

comments.text: How did you connect the different swatches of fabric?
comments.author: th3chainrule

comments.text:
I haven't connected different parts yet. If you want to create something bigger than your printer is capable, with this type of fabric it would be hard to connect individual printed parts to a bigger one because of the compact design. Please watch Devins video, there's a NASA derived fabric that can be connected with a 3D pen into a huge piece.
If you want to combine a smaller piece of fabric with some other thing just use the stl or export a version from OpenSCAD and combine it in your 3D modelling program.

description.text:
One of the most common 3D printing issues is nozzle clogging. Filament monitor alarms 3D printer user when material jams and plastic is no longer extruded. Quick action after detecting this problem may save the print and avoid loose of even tens of hours printing.

This filament monitor is unique since it is based on low-cost and easily available parts. Total cost is only about 5 USD!

Due to the application of described gear 3D printing becomes quicker, cheaper and less frustrating processes.

More information and step by step instruction to build the filament monitor (See Appendix) you can find here:

http://www.researchgate.net/publication/321335097_The_design_of_the_low-cost_alarm_preventing_3D_printing_from_nozzle_clog_problems

If you find my work useful please cite my paper or add the URL above to your website, blog or forum post. I am PhD Student, and citations or article reads prove to university authorities that my projects are valuable.
https://youtu.be/1p3SE7siK2I

comments.text: If you increase the number of slits signal is generated more frequent, and you can print with lower speed with no alarm. However, in this project I focus on lower cost and simplicity. This filament monitor should be as simple as possible. I use the fishing bite indicator as the filament monitor so people that don’t know much about electronics are able to assemble all part on their own. Real time monitoring is a feature available in more advanced (more expensive and more complicated) filament monitors.

Add a bunch of BB pellets. Mine takes 42.
Align Top.
Add Reel.

This is a customisable script that can produce templates for area of effect (AOE) events (blasts, spells, beams...).

title: 1u switch bracket for HP 1400 24g procurve switch

description.text:
Building on the bracket that was designed by user rob0tuss1n, i had to adjust the hole spacing to fit this tiny procurve switch. I picked the procurve 1400 up for $20 at a local recycling place. Its gigabit which is what i needed, and has a very small profile (depth). This was necessary, as i am just using a normal 2U patch panel rack for both the cabiling and the switch, so the switch needed to fit in there.

I ended up reversing the brackets and having the switch stick out 1-2 inches to provide clearance on the back for the power cord.

The spacing on the model if i can recall from memory was 11mm from the top and bottom to the holes. 22mm between holes, both left and right and up and down, and i believe 20mm from the front of the bracket to the first hole. (all distances measured from the centre of the holes.)

rob0tuss1n's bracket was a spacing of 25mm between holes.

I ended up using 6x32 1/2 inch bolts as mounting hardware to fasten the bracket to the side of the switch.

The only problem i had was that the rack holes for the rack screws was a little bit tight, so if i did a version 4, i would make them 1mm wider. the rack screws work fine now, but the fact that its an oval should mean that i can adjust while racking. I cannot with this mount as the rack screw digs into the mounting hole making left/right play not possible. The holes for the mounting the switch could use to be countersunk as well. Oh well, its very much good enough, and not bad for a few hours work!

print_settings.Notes:: Must use 0.05mm layer heights

description.text:
This model will allow for quick exposure calibration on a dlp printer in a single print. It is required that 0.05mm layer heights are used and that the Gcode is written such that exposure times will decrease for the last 20 layers. When finished a filled in square will represent an exposure time that is sufficient to cure a layer of resin.

My Gcode to achieve the variation in exposure times is included as a .txt file. Copy and paste it into the preslice Gcode window in creation workshop. If you use this Gcode you will need to set your exposure time in the options tab of the slicing profile to 0msec. The way to interpret the key line of code which is:
{($CURSLICE >= 20)?{($CURSLICE < 140)?;<Delay> 10000:;<Delay> %d(10000 - 330 * ($CURSLICE - 139))}:}
Interpretation: If current layer is greater than 20 then check if current layer is less than 140. If yes then cure for 10000msec otherwise cure for (10000 - 330)msec and decrease cure times by 330msec every layer afterwards.

title: BIQU Hot Bed MOSFET Power Module BOX

description.text:
This is an enclosure/box with lid and and openings for air cooling to protect the MOS module and operate it conveniently simply opening the lid. This is designed for v1.3 modules, these have a lower MOSFET heatsink that is needlessly oversized in previous versions.

Anyway if you have a previous version you can try to break some air vent gaps from the lid and try, otherwise the lid wouldn't close. Several lids provided, choose your favourite.

Fixing screws & hexa nuts 4x M3x10. Drill yourself the holes for fixing it to the chassis as you need. No support required. ABS print recommended. 30% infill. Once printed clean up / sand a bit the hinge attachments and press fit gently the lid to the box inserting first one of the lid pins, then the other. The two teeth of the closing of the lid are smaller, sand it a bit till you feel the lid closes/opens as you want (not too tight).

Base doesn't provide mounting holes, drill yours according to your needs.

These modules are highly recommended, as it contains NPQ030N06 power MOSFET capable of 200+ amps, a very low voltage drop, and optocoupler. It works COOL even at 25Amp. Easily found below $5. Nice update if you have a powerful DC hotbed. Mine works cool at 24v/18A. I was tired of relays and bad quality SSR's till I found this. All my machines have one of this now. I love it.

Included used module pic as a reference.

Enjoy.

UPDATE (29-NOV-2017):Lid vent holes were misaligned 1mm. This didn't affect lid functionality. Anyway lid model and FreeCAD sources updated. Added three more lid models. If you want to see LED's I recommend to print the lid in clear ABS. Increased M3 hex nut holes diameter. Pics of one of my builds. Added a groove to the lids to help using your nail to open the box.
